awd_titl_txt: SBIR Phase I:  Multiple Access Laser Communication Terminals for Optical Orbital Hotspots
awd_abstract_narration:
The broader impact/commercial potential of this Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) Phase I project lies in the development of an Optical Orbital Hotspot network that will enhance satellite data collection and utilization. This innovation is projected to make small satellites operating more efficient and accessible, thus empowering businesses, agencies, and new entrants. The expected result is an increase in data generation and transfer, improving connectivity to cloud-based services and Low Earth Orbit (LEO) space-based platforms. By decreasing the technical and cost barriers to LEO access, rapid innovation will be enabled, leveraging existing aerospace research. This development is aligned with a growing market, with the satellite laser communication market expected to reach $4.1B by 2031. The commercial implications are vast, including opportunities to address an even larger satellite ground station market, with the potential to enable transformational opportunities across various sectors.

This SBIR Phase I project proposes to develop and refine the technology for an Optical Orbital Hotspot network integration and implement advanced beam steering technologies. The primary challenges lie in the creation of multi-access lasercom terminals (MALT) and the development of orbital optical hotspot technology. The research will mature the optical designs of the MALT and compact user lasercom terminal systems (micro-LCT). Research and objectives to be addressed range from operations development to preliminary hardware design.  The anticipated technical results will include the establishment of orbital models, multibeam steering technology development, interface and requirements definition, and design for the MALT and micro-LCT systems. These efforts will collectively solve the 'last mile problem' for small size, weight, power, and cost satellites, enhancing capabilities and lowering high data rate communication barriers in the Earth observing systems market.

This award reflects NSF's statutory mission and has been deemed worthy of support through evaluation using the Foundation's intellectual merit and broader impacts review criteria.

1.2 Report Executive Summary

This report outlines the outcomes of Phase I of the SpaceRake, Inc. (SpaceRake) Optical Orbital Hotspot (OOH) development effort, funded by the National Science Foundation (NSF). SpaceRake aims to revolutionize small satellite communication in Low Earth Orbit (LEO) by addressing the current bandwidth and cost limitations of radio frequency (RF) systems. By leveraging optical laser communication technologies, SpaceRake will provide small satellites with continuous broadband access to emerging orbiting optical backbone networks. This capability will enable data downlink capacities to increase from 50 GB/day to over 8 TB/day, while simultaneously reducing data transmission costs by more than an order of magnitude.

The central innovation of this effort lies in the study of an architecture (See Fig. 1) built from two key technologies:

  1. Multi-Access Laser Communication Terminals (MALTs): These allow simultaneous connections to multiple user satellites within a shared service volume, dramatically improving network efficiency.

  2. The Puck: A miniaturized, low size, weight, power, and cost (SWaP-C) optical terminal that connects small satellites to the OOH, enabling high-bandwidth, low-latency communication.

 

 

 

Figure 1: Diagram of the SpaceRake Optical Orbital Hotspot (OOH) architecture, illustrating the interaction between "Puck" terminals, a router spacecraft, and the global optical backbone network. This configuration enables high-bandwidth, low-latency communication for small satellites using modular, low SWaP-C designs.

 

2. Accomplishments

In recent years, small satellites (smallsats) have become a cornerstone of modern space applications, enabling a wide range of activities, from Earth observation to scientific research and communications. However, one of the most significant bottlenecks for smallsat missions is the ability to efficiently downlink the large volumes of data they generate. Current radio frequency (RF) communication systems, which dominate the smallsat landscape, are bandwidth-limited, providing a daily data downlink capacity of only 50 GB. This limitation constrains the scientific and commercial potential of smallsat missions, as it creates barriers to real-time data access, rapid decision-making, and cloud-based analysis.

Emerging optical laser communication systems offer an exciting opportunity to address this bottleneck. These systems provide vastly higher bandwidth and more secure data links than RF systems. However, the integration of optical communication technologies into smallsat missions is currently limited by the large SWaP-C requirements of existing laser communication terminals. Additionally, the point-to-point architecture of many optical systems poses significant scalability challenges, as each satellite requires a dedicated terminal to connect into the emerging optical backbone networks. 

The SpaceRake project aims to overcome these challenges by introducing Optical Orbiting Hotspots (OOHs) - a network architecture that enables smallsats to access high-bandwidth laser communication networks via shared access points. Inspired by terrestrial WiFi hotspots, the architecture investigated on this grant (shown in Fig. 2) would allow small satellites to use highly miniaturized laser communication terminals. Much like the WiFi chip in a laptop, these terminals would be capable of high bandwidth communication in a small form factor, but only at short range. The SpaceRake multi-access router would carry longer range terminals capable of achieving high bandwidth links into the high capacity backbone networks, such as the Space Development Agency’s (SDA) Transport Layer. This configuration reduces the SWaP-C burden for individual spacecraft, allowing operators to opt for a commercial service for connectivity to the greater network. 

 

Figure 2: "String of Pearls" configuration of the SpaceRake Optical Orbital Hotspot (OOH) architecture, illustrating a 5-degree full-angle field of regard (FoR) for the router spacecraft and customer satellites separated by 1-degree True Anomaly. This design enables efficient coverage and high-bandwidth connectivity across a distributed satellite network.

In this phase 1 effort, supported by NSF funding (award number 2319654), SpaecRake explored the commercial viability of various architectures through tradespace analysis and modeling. 

The primary objective of this study was to evaluate the feasibility and technical performance of the OOH architecture. This involved developing a comprehensive trade space analysis to assess the performance and scalability of different configurations, including the interplay between the multi-access router and the miniaturized laser terminals (the Pucks). By simulating a variety of architectural parameters—such as coverage area, data rates, link range, and system costs—the study aimed to identify the optimal balance between technical performance and commercial viability. Additionally, the effort sought to define the system requirements necessary for supporting scalable, multi-user connectivity within the service volume of an OOH network node.

A secondary objective was to explore and refine the enabling technologies critical to the success of the SpaceRake architecture. This included the evaluation of various beam steering technologies—such as microelectromechanical system (MEMS) fast steering mirror (FSM), Voice Coil, and Gimbaled Flat mechanisms—for use in the Multi-Access Laser Communication Terminal (MALT). Through this process, SpaceRake aimed to establish a preliminary design for both the MALT and Puck systems, grounded in validated link budget calculations and trade-off analyses. The outcomes of this study inform the future development of a high-bandwidth, cost-effective optical communication service for smallsat operators.
